  <h1>AD Recon AI Agent</h1>

  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>An autonomous Active Directory reconnaissance agent combines a local LLM with a tool registry and a RAG knowledge base to enumerate, analyze, and prioritize attack paths without cloud API dependencies. The agent runs the standard red team AD recon workflow — LDAP enumeration, ACL analysis, SPN discovery, BloodHound path queries — but drives each step autonomously, interprets the output, and decides what to enumerate next.</p>
  <p>This page covers the full design: model selection, agent architecture, tool implementation, RAG setup, optional fine-tuning, and deployment packaging. The stack is designed to fit on an 8GB RAM device (RPi 5, Jetson, laptop) and run entirely offline.</p>

  <h2>Train Your Own Model vs Use Ollama</h2>
  <p>The right answer for a lightweight, deployable agent is almost always <strong>Ollama + a small pre-trained model + RAG</strong>. Here's why:</p>

  <h3>Why Not Train From Scratch</h3>
  <pre><code># Training a language model from scratch requires:
# - Hundreds to thousands of GPUs for weeks (GPT-3 scale: ~$4.6M compute cost)
# - Trillions of tokens of training data
# - Deep ML infrastructure expertise
# - Months of work
#
# This is what Mistral, Meta, Google, and Qwen teams do.
# It is not a viable path for a red team tool.
#
# Even "small" models like Llama 3.2 (3B params) were trained on:
# - ~9 trillion tokens
# - Thousands of A100 GPU-hours
# - Professionally curated + filtered datasets
#
# Starting from scratch produces an incoherent model.
# The base models available for free are already excellent — build on them.</code></pre>

  <h3>Fine-Tuning — When and How</h3>
  <p>Fine-tuning adapts an existing pre-trained model on a small, domain-specific dataset. It improves the model's behavior on specific tasks without the compute cost of training from scratch. For an AD recon agent, fine-tuning can improve: LDAP filter generation accuracy, BloodHound Cypher query quality, and interpretation of AD output formats.</p>
  <pre><code># Fine-tuning options ranked by effort vs reward:
#
# 1. QLoRA fine-tune (recommended if you want domain improvement):
#    - Works on: RTX 3090/4090 (24GB VRAM), or rented A100 (~$2-3/hr)
#    - Dataset size needed: 500-3000 examples
#    - Training time: 1-4 hours for 7B model
#    - Tooling: Unsloth (fastest, memory-efficient), PEFT + Transformers
#    - Output: LoRA adapter weights → merge → GGUF → load in Ollama
#
# 2. RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) — much easier, often better:
#    - No GPU training required
#    - Add a knowledge base of AD attack paths, LDAP filters, BloodHound queries
#    - Model retrieves relevant context at inference time
#    - Updateable without retraining
#    - Better for factual lookups (specific attack paths, CVE details)
#
# 3. Prompt engineering + few-shot examples:
#    - Zero effort, zero cost
#    - Surprisingly effective for structured tasks
#    - Works well for models like qwen2.5-coder that already know LDAP/PowerShell
#
# Recommendation for v1:
# Start with RAG + prompt engineering.
# Add QLoRA fine-tune in v2 if the model generates incorrect LDAP/Cypher consistently.

# Fine-tune dataset format (JSONL, Alpaca style):
# &#123;
#   "instruction": "Generate an LDAP query to find all users with unconstrained delegation",
#   "input": "Domain: corp.local",
#   "output": "(&(objectCategory=person)(objectClass=user)(userAccountControl:1.2.840.113556.1.4.803:=524288))"
# &#125;
# Build 500+ examples covering: LDAP filters, output parsing, attack path reasoning</code></pre>

